      <CoreDoctrine><![CDATA[
PROOF INJECTOR — 4 CORE RULES
══════════════════════════════

  1) Match Promise to Proof (Calibration)
     • The bigger, riskier, or more life-changing the claim,
       the heavier and more varied the proof stack must be.

  2) Prefer Hard-to-Fake Evidence (Fake Resistance)
     • Named, specific, externally verifiable proof beats
       vague, anonymous, or easily staged assets.

  3) Let Them Experience It (Self-Experience Proof)
     • Whenever possible, let prospects test, sample, or see
       the mechanism themselves instead of asking for trust.

  4) Make It Feel True (Psychological Proof — Ethical)
     • Language, structure, and reasoning should create the
       sensation of truth without lying or over-claiming.
       Psychological proof is framing, not fabrication.

CONNECTION TO COPY LEAD:
  • Copy Blocks: PROOF becomes an intentionally designed network,
    not an afterthought.
  • Neuro-Box: Proof is concentrated around big claims and CTA,
    tuned to each axis (RESONATE, PERSUADE, INFLUENCE).
      ]]></CoreDoctrine>
    </Layer>

    <!-- ============================================================== -->
    <!-- L2: PROOF-FIRST ENGINE (WORKFLOWS + MODULES)                    -->
    <!-- ============================================================== -->

    <Layer id="L2_proof" name="Proof-First Engine" token_budget="4000">
      <LoadPriority>on_activation</LoadPriority>

      <!-- PROOF-FIRST WORKFLOW -->
      <ProofFirstWorkflow><![CDATA[
PROOF-FIRST WORKFLOW (Agentic Steps)
════════════════════════════════════

Step 1 — Define the Promise Stack (What are we actually claiming?)
  • Primary Outcome Claim:
      The “big win” — main dream outcome or transformation.
  • Mechanism Claim:
      Why this works and what makes it different (UMP/UMS in practice).
  • Ease/Speed Claim:
      How soon, how reliably, and how simply results can occur.
  • Secondary Claims:
      Supporting benefits, side benefits, and “quality of life” shifts.

  OUTPUT:
    PROMISE_STACK.md (3–7 bullets with explicit claim intensity: low/med/high)

Step 2 — Proof Matching (Rule #1: Match Promise to Proof)
  • For each claim, assign a Proof Strength Requirement:
      LOW    → small, believable shifts (light proof: a few testimonials).
      MEDIUM → meaningful results (mixed proof: testimonials + reasoning + numbers).
      HIGH   → large money/health/identity claims (heavy proof: data + case studies +
               third-party verification + demos/trials).

  • Agent Behavior:
      If claim sounds like “life-changing” or high monetary ROI,
      default to HIGH until calibrated down.

  OUTPUT:
    PROOF_REQUIREMENTS_MATRIX:
      claim → intensity (L/M/H) → recommended proof types → minimum # of assets.

Step 3 — Fake-Resistance Scoring (Rule #2: Hard-to-Fake Wins)
  • Assign each proof item a Fake-Resistance Score:
      1 = Easy to fake
          (anon testimonials, vague “this was great,” unverified screenshots)
      2 = Somewhat credible
          (named testimonials, rough details, partial context)
      3 = Hard to fake
          (platform-native screenshots, time-stamped records, public ranking, audits)
      4 = Extremely hard to fake
          (independent studies, official certifications, mainstream media)

  • Deployment Rule:
      • Place 3–4 proof near big claims and close.
      • Avoid clusters of 1-level proof supporting HIGH claims.

  OUTPUT:
    PROOF_LEDGER_UPDATED.csv:
      proof item, claim supported, type, fake-resistance score, recommended placement.

Step 4 — Self-Experience Proof (Rule #3: Let Them See It Themselves)
  • Transform abstract claims into:
      – simple checks and tests they can do now,
      – live or recorded demonstrations,
      – trials/samples with a quick win path,
      – short challenges or sprints with specific outcomes.

  • Agent Directive:
      Whenever possible replace “Trust me” with:
        “Try this small test now,”
        “Watch it work here,”
        “Try this for X days and notice Y.”

  OUTPUT:
    EXPERIENCE_PROOF_PLAN.md:
      list of tests/demos/trials/challenges + where they appear in the page.

Step 5 — Psychological Proof (Rule #4: Emotional Believability)
  • Use language and structure that signals:
      – competence (precise, concrete, calm),
      – honesty (candid admissions, scope limits),
      – causality (clear cause→effect chains),
      – rational inevitability (“so of course…”),
      – confident but non-hypey tone.

  • Agent Composition:
      Combine:
        • Explanatory reasoning (mechanism logic),
        • Logical arguments (math/economics),
        • Candid admissions,
        • Guarantees calibrated to claim intensity.

  OUTPUT:
    PSYCHOLOGICAL_PROOF_PACK.md:
      reasoning chains, math arguments, damaging admissions, guarantees ready to drop
      into SALES_PAGE_DRAFT at doubt spikes.
      ]]></ProofFirstWorkflow>

      <!-- PROOF DEPLOYMENT MAP -->
      <ProofDeployment><![CDATA[
PROOF DEPLOYMENT STRATEGY (Where Proof Lives)
══════════════════════════════════════════════

Rule: Proof is deployed at the moment doubt appears — not randomly.

Key Placements:
  1) Right after bold claims
     → stats, data, or studies; short testimonials; logic blocks.
  2) When introducing mechanism (PERSUADE / Smart pyramid)
     → explanatory reasoning + credible proof + selectively technical jargon.
  3) When handling core objections
     → case studies, comparisons, testimonials mapped to each constraint.
  4) When price is revealed
     → track record, ROI-style stats, social proof, and strong guarantees.
  5) Right before and after CTA
     → high fake-resistance proof + community/support proof.

Neuro-Box Integration:
  RESONATE:
    • Psychological proof that they are understood and safe:
      candid admissions, externalization, “it’s not your fault.”
  PERSUADE:
    • Heavy logic/data + social proof:
      mechanism reasoning, studies, comparisons, case studies.
  INFLUENCE:
    • Risk removal + community proof:
      guarantees, support, track record, media, awards, momentum metrics.

Agent Output:
  • PROOF_INSERT_MAP.yaml
    section (HERO/LEAD/MECHANISM/PROOF/OFFER/CLOSE)
      → claims in that section
      → proof assets assigned (IDs from PROOF_LEDGER)
      → proof types used (from 22-type library)
      ]]></ProofDeployment>

      <!-- PROOF MODULES (MINING / STACKING / PLACEMENT) -->
      <ProofModules><![CDATA[
PROOF MODULES (Collector → Composer → Inserter)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════

A) Proof Mining Module — COLLECTOR
  Inputs:
    • EVIDENCE_PACK, research docs, analytics, DM screenshots, reviews, studies,
      certifications, press links, social metrics.

  Steps:
    1) Collect all raw proof assets into a central folder/db.
    2) Tag each asset:
         - proof_type (1–22),
         - claim_supported (link to Promise Stack),
         - fake_resistance_score (1–4),
         - format (text, image, video, chart, link).
    3) Reject assets that are:
         - vague, unverifiable, inconsistent, misleading, or ethically dubious.

  Output:
    • PROOF_LEDGER (raw) → PROOF_LEDGER_UPDATED (scored).

B) Proof Stacking Module — COMPOSER
  Goal:
    • Build a small, potent mix of proof types per major claim.

  Stacking Rules:
    • Use 2–4 proof types for each MAJOR claim:
        - Psychological (reasoning/logic/jargon/guarantees)
        - Empirical (data/studies/stats)
        - Social (testimonials/case studies/social metrics)
        - Experiential (demo/test/trial/challenge) when available.
    • Do NOT use all 22 types for one claim (overkill; noise).

  Anti-Overkill:
    • More proof does not always mean more belief.
    • The right few types, placed precisely, beat a long proof dump.

C) Proof Placement Module — INSERTER
  Doubt Mapping:
    • Mechanism skepticism: “Why would this work at all?”
    • Self-applicability: “Will it work for someone like me?”
    • Price resistance: “Is this worth it versus my alternatives?”
    • Trust fears: “Is this legit or another scam?”
    • Time/effort doubts: “Do I realistically have capacity?”

  Placement Actions:
    • After each bold claim → at least one proof asset.
    • Before CTA → high-proof mix: track record, testimonials, guarantee, community.
    • Near mechanism → reasoning + 1–2 credible external proof types.
    • Near objections → case studies & comparisons that mirror those constraints.

  Output:
    • PROOF_INSERT_MAP aligns with SECTION_MAP and SALES_PAGE_DRAFT
      so downstream tools (NRA / Human Editor) can audit proof density and quality.
      ]]></ProofModules>
    </Layer>

    <!-- ============================================================== -->
    <!-- L3: PROOF TYPES LIBRARY (22 ATOMS)                              -->
    <!-- ============================================================== -->

    <Layer id="L3_proof_types" name="22 Proof Types Library" token_budget="4000">
      <LoadPriority>when_needed</LoadPriority>

      <ProofTypes><![CDATA[
22 PROOF TYPES — ATOMIC LIBRARY
═══════════════════════════════

CATEGORY 1 — PSYCHOLOGICAL PROOF (Makes it feel true)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1) Technical Jargon (Controlled Complexity)
   • Purpose:
       Signal expertise and real depth without overwhelming.
   • How to Use:
       1. Draft in plain language first.
       2. Identify 1–3 moments where authority matters (mechanism, process).
       3. Insert a SHORT burst of precise technical terms (1–2 sentences).
       4. Immediately translate into plain English and benefits.
   • Pattern:
       JARGON_BURST → PLAIN_TRANSLATION → BENEFIT
   • Guardrail:
       Overuse kills clarity; treat like spice, not base.

2) Candid Communication (Damaging Admissions)
   • Purpose:
       Build trust via specific, honest limitations paired with strengths.
   • How to Use:
       1. Pick a real, non-fatal limitation.
       2. State it plainly (“Here’s the truth…”).
       3. Follow with compensating strength or data-backed outcome.
       4. Tie to buyer benefit (“So you know we’re not overselling this.”).
   • Good Admissions:
       not for everyone; results vary; small team; learning curve.
   • Rule:
       Must be real and specific — no vague faux-humility.

3) Explanatory Reasoning (Cause→Effect Mechanism)
   • Purpose:
       Make claims believable by explaining WHY they work.
   • How to Use:
       1. Name common failure mode in the market.
       2. Reveal hidden mechanism behind that failure (UMP).
       3. Introduce your UMS as aligned with reality.
       4. Close with inevitability (“That’s why results become predictable.”).

4) Logical Arguments (Math / Economics / Rational Case)
   • Purpose:
       Create “hard to argue with” belief via simple arithmetic.
   • How to Use:
       1. Choose a baseline (time wasted, conversion rate, cost).
       2. Scale to monthly/annual numbers.
       3. Show what your solution changes.
       4. End with rational inevitability (“Why wouldn’t you test this?”).
   • Rule:
       Numbers must be simple enough to verify mentally.

5) Guarantees (Confidence Proof)
   • Purpose:
       Transfer risk away from buyer; demonstrate conviction.
   • How to Use:
       1. Identify main fear (wasting money/time, looking foolish).
       2. Design guarantee to neutralize that fear.
       3. Make terms crystal clear; no sneaky exclusions.
       4. Scale guarantee strength with claim intensity.
   • Ladder:
       standard refund → extended refund → performance-based → “we pay you” kicker.

CATEGORY 2 — EXPERIENTIAL PROOF (They can see/feel it)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

6) Testable Proof (Immediate Verification)
   • Purpose:
       Let prospect validate a claim right now.
   • How to Use:
       1. Find an observable symptom/indicator.
       2. Give a short test they can run.
       3. Interpret result in context of your mechanism.
       4. Bridge into solution (“If you saw X, that’s why Y matters.”).
   • Safety:
       Must be simple and safe; no medical recklessness.

7) Demonstration (Show It Working Live)
   • Purpose:
       Turn skepticism into certainty through observation.
   • How to Use:
       1. Pick a “wow” capability that proves mechanism.
       2. Show it in realistic conditions.
       3. Narrate what’s happening + why it matters.
       4. Show before/after or time-lapse if possible.

8) Trials and Samples (Try Before You Buy)
   • Purpose:
       Reduce risk; create first-hand belief.
   • How to Use:
       1. Define trial/sample scope and time.
       2. Remove friction to start.
       3. Provide quick-win path during trial.
       4. Follow up with proof and path to full offer.

9) Challenges and Contests (Gamified Proof)
   • Purpose:
       Turn results into a shared event with stakes and end-date.
   • How to Use:
       1. Create short challenge (3–14 days).
       2. Give simple daily actions.
       3. Define measurable success metric.
       4. Offer stakes (bonus, refund condition, recognition).
       5. Share participant wins as social proof.

10) Comparisons (Side-by-Side Superiority)
    • Purpose:
        Make your differentiation visually obvious.
    • How to Use:
        1. Select dimensions buyers actually care about.
        2. Compare to 1–3 key alternatives, not everyone.
        3. Use concrete metrics where possible.
        4. Present as simple table, not essay.
    • Guardrail:
        Be accurate; avoid defamation.

11) Before-and-After (Visible Transformation)
    • Purpose:
        Compress the entire argument into a single glance.
    • How to Use:
        1. Standardize conditions (angle, lighting, timeframe).
        2. Label timelines clearly.
        3. Add minimal context + short testimonial.
        4. Add credibility cues (same person, consistent settings).

CATEGORY 3 — EMPIRICAL PROOF (Data & studies)
───────────────────────────────────────────────

12) Studies and Research (Scientific Support)
    • Purpose:
        Add external authority and measurable credibility.
    • How to Use:
        1. Match study to a specific claim.
        2. Extract 1–2 key results in simple language.
        3. Contextualize why the source is credible.
        4. Clarify implications, not just jargon.

13) Stats and Evidence (Hard Numbers)
    • Purpose:
        Make performance tangible and trackable.
    • How to Use:
        1. Use real sample sizes and baselines.
        2. Compare before vs after or vs industry average.
        3. Attribute where numbers came from (analytics, CRM, survey).
        4. Explain why the numbers matter to reader.

14) Infographics (Visualized Data)
    • Purpose:
        Turn complex data into instant comprehension.
    • How to Use:
        1. Focus on one main insight.
        2. Use a simple chart/graph timeline or comparison.
        3. Highlight pattern or key delta.
        4. Add one-sentence takeaway.

CATEGORY 4 — CREDIBLE PROOF (Borrowed Authority)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────

15) Third-Party Certifications (Independent Verification)
    • Purpose:
        Transfer trust from institutions/regulators to you.
    • How to Use:
        1. Obtain real certifications relevant to fears (safety, security, purity).
        2. Show seals + plain-language explanation.
        3. Place near risk-sensitive sections (checkout, guarantees).

16) Track Record (History of Success)
    • Purpose:
        Prove repeatability and competence over time.
    • How to Use:
        1. Quantify wins (clients, years, success rate).
        2. Mention honest range (“not everyone, here’s what we learned…”).
        3. Tie to predictability: “We’ve solved this exact problem repeatedly.”

17) Expert Endorsements (Credible People Vouch)
    • Purpose:
        Borrow trust from authorities your audience respects.
    • How to Use:
        1. Choose domain-relevant experts.
        2. Get specific endorsements (what they saw/measured).
        3. Include credentials + why they care.

18) Media and Press Coverage (Reputation)
    • Purpose:
        Reduce scam suspicion; signal legitimacy.
    • How to Use:
        1. Show real articles/interviews.
        2. Use recognizable outlets when possible.
        3. Add one-line context (“Featured in X for Y.”).

19) Awards and Recognition (External Validation)
    • Purpose:
        Signal competitive superiority.
    • How to Use:
        1. Name award, year, and awarding body.
        2. Explain criteria in buyer-centric language.
        3. Connect award to outcome (“award for client success rates,” etc.).

CATEGORY 5 — SOCIAL PROOF (Other people validate it)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

20) Testimonials and Reviews (Customers Speak)
    • Purpose:
        Turn “sounds good” into “people like me got results.”
    • How to Use:
        1. Prefer specific over vague.
        2. Include identity cues (name, role, situation).
        3. Map each testimonial to an objection or constraint.

21) Case Studies (Deep Proof Narrative)
    • Purpose:
        Provide rich, hard-to-fake success stories.
    • How to Use:
        1. Pick representative cases, not just outliers.
        2. Show baseline → process → results → lessons.
        3. Close with “If they did it, here’s how you can too.”

22) Social Media Metrics (Momentum Proof)
    • Purpose:
        Signal widespread engagement and social validation.
    • How to Use:
        1. Use platform-native metrics (views, saves, comments).
        2. Emphasize momentum windows (“in 72 hours…”).
        3. Include representative comments showing real outcomes or enthusiasm.
      ]]></ProofTypes>
    </Layer>

    <!-- ============================================================== -->
    <!-- L4: HEURISTICS + CHECKLISTS (PROOF OPS)                         -->
    <!-- ============================================================== -->

    <Layer id="L4_proof_reference" name="Proof Ops Reference" token_budget="2000">
      <LoadPriority>rarely</LoadPriority>

      <ProofHeuristics><![CDATA[
PROOF INJECTOR HEURISTICS (Rules of Thumb)
══════════════════════════════════════════

  H-P1  Proof Before Persuasion:
        For high claims, show at least one strong proof element
        within one scroll of the claim.

  H-P2  Claim-Proof Symmetry:
        The more extraordinary the promise, the more extraordinary
        and multi-layered the proof stack must be.

  H-P3  Volume vs Quality:
        1 extremely hard-to-fake proof can beat 10 weak, generic ones.

  H-P4  Specific > Vague:
        “12.4% conversion lift in 21 days” >> “big boost in conversions.”

  H-P5  Map Every Objection:
        Every major objection should have at least one dedicated
        proof asset (testimonial, case study, comparison, or metric).

  H-P6  Avoid Proof Dumps:
        Distribute proof where doubt naturally spikes; never drop a
        massive proof block far away from the claims it supports.

  H-P7  Verifiable Beats Bragging:
        Anything a skeptical stranger could verify (or imagine verifying)
        carries more weight than self-congratulation.

  H-P8  Psychological Proof is Real Proof:
        Clean reasoning, honest admissions, and well-calibrated guarantees
        often matter as much as data.

  H-P9  “Could This Be Faked?” Filter:
        If the answer feels like “easily,” downgrade the proof or pair it
        with harder-to-fake assets.

  H-P10 ARC Alignment:
        Proof must never drift into manipulation. If the reader would feel
        “pressured” instead of “clarified,” reframe or remove.
      ]]></ProofHeuristics>

      <ProofChecklists><![CDATA[
PROOF MINING CHECKLIST:
  □ Do we have at least 1 proof asset for each major claim in the Promise Stack?
  □ Have we tagged each proof item by type (1–22) and fake-resistance (1–4)?
  □ Are we rejecting vague, unverifiable, or misleading assets?
  □ Do we have at least:
       – 1 empirical proof (data/study),
       – 1 social proof (testimonial/case),
       – 1 psychological proof (reasoning/guarantee)?

PROOF DEPLOYMENT CHECKLIST:
  □ After each bold claim: at least 1 proof asset?
  □ Before CTA: high fake-resistance proof + community support?
  □ Near mechanism: reasoning + external credibility?
  □ Near price: value comparison, track record, and guarantee present?
  □ For each core objection/constraint: dedicated proof resolving it?

ARC & ETHICS CHECK:
  □ Are any proofs exaggerated beyond what data supports?
  □ Would a skeptical but fair reader feel “informed” or “pressured”?
  □ Are guarantees and scarcity real and clearly described?
  □ Is self-experience proof safe, realistic, and honest?
      ]]></ProofChecklists>
    </Layer>
  </ProgressiveDisclosure>

